s a thug of peripheral interest. Until now, only the most salacious bits of the Life of Barsauma-a fascinating collection of miracles that Barsauma undertook across the Near East-had been translated. This pioneering study includes the first full translation of the Life and a series of studies by scholars employing a range of methods to illuminate the text from different angles and contexts. This is the authoritative source on this influential figure in the history of the church and his life, travels, and relations with other religious groups.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aChristianity and antisemitismxHistory. 0aSyriac Christian saintsvBiography. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  a5th century.  aalexander the sleepless.  aantiquity.  aantisemitism.  aarchimandrite.  aascetic.  abarsauma.  abishops.  achristianity.  achurch history.  acloister.  adiscrimination.  aeastern church.  aeudocia.  ahagiography.  ahate.  ahistory.  aholy land.  aholy men.  ajerusalem.  alife of barsauma.  amiddle east.  amiracles.  amonk.  anear east.  anonfiction.  apalestine.  apilgrimage.  aprejudice.  areligion.  areligious figures.  areligious groups.  areligious persecution.  asamaritans.  aspirituality.  asyria.  atemple mount.1 aCaner, Daniel F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorcoran, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrijvers, Jan Willem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHahn, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHahn, Johannes, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHorn, Cornelia B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKiperwasser,